        },
        {
          "id": 22494,
          "text": "<p style=\"margin-left:-9px\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Escherichia coli</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 22495,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Vibrio cholerae</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"margin-left:-9px; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 10-year-old boy with a history of beta-thalassemia major presents to the pediatric clinic for a routine follow-up. His parents express concern about a recent episode of acute gastroenteritis with abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea. The boy has been on chronic transfusion therapy, and his recent lab tests indicate iron overload despite chelation therapy. Considering his underlying condition and the clinical presentation, which of the following organisms is he at increased risk of being infected with?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4944622",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35222,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Yersinia enterocolitica</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Patients with <strong>beta-thalassemia major </strong>are often on <strong>chronic blood transfusions</strong>, which can lead to <strong>secondary hemochromatosis or iron overload</strong>. <strong>Yersinia enterocolitica </strong>thrives in <strong>iron-rich environments </strong>and can cause <strong>gastroenteritis </strong>with symptoms like <strong>fever, abdominal pain</strong>, and <strong>bloody diarrhea</strong>, particularly in patients with <strong>iron overload states such as thalassemia</strong>. Thus, patients with beta-thalassemia and iron overload are at increased risk for infection with Yersinia enterocolitica.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Campylobacter jejuni </strong>causes <strong>gastroenteritis</strong>, but there is no specific association with iron overload states.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Escherichia coli </strong>is a common <strong>cause of gastroenteritis </strong>but does not have a particular predilection for patients with iron overload.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Vibrio cholerae </strong>causes <strong>cholera</strong>, which is characterized by <strong>profuse watery diarrhea</strong>, not bloody diarrhea, and is not linked to iron overload.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Patients with <strong>beta-thalassemia major</strong>, often undergoing <strong>chronic blood transfusions</strong>, are <strong>susceptible to secondary hemochromatosis or iron overload</strong>. <strong>Yersinia enterocolitica</strong>, a <strong>bacterium </strong>that <strong>thrives in iron-rich environments</strong>, poses a significant risk to these patients. It can <strong>cause gastroenteritis</strong>, manifesting as <strong>fever, abdominal pain, and bloody diarrhea</strong>, especially in those with conditions like thalassemia that lead to iron overload.&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:&nbsp;</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Harrison Principles of Internal Medicine19th/p1076, Apurba Sastry&rsquo;s Essentials of Medical Microbiology 1/e p315</span></span></strong></p>",
