        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 32-year-old female with a history of recurrent urinary tract infections (UTIs) inquires about dietary modifications that could help prevent future episodes. She has no known drug allergies and is not currently on any prophylactic antibiotics. Which of the following beverages is most likely to reduce the risk of recurrent UTIs in this patient?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6712108",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35220,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Cranberry juice.</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Cranberry juice </strong>has been shown to <strong>help prevent urinary tract infections </strong>(UTIs). It contains <strong>proanthocyanidins </strong>that can <strong>inhibit the adhesion of E. coli bacteria </strong>to the <strong>urothelial lining of the bladder and urethra</strong>, <strong>reducing </strong>the <strong>risk of infection. </strong>While <strong>cranberry juice </strong>is <strong>not a substitute for antimicrobial therapy in active infection</strong>, it may be a useful adjunct in the prevention of recurrent UTIs.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Grape juice - </span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">There is <strong>no evidence </strong>that <strong>grape juice </strong>has a significant effect on UTI prevention<strong>.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Raspberry juice -</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Like grape juice, there is <strong>no evidence </strong>to suggest raspberry juice can prevent UTIs.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Orange juice -</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> While a healthy beverage, orange juice has <strong>not been shown to prevent UTIs</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Cranberry juice </strong>helps to <strong>prevent recurrent urinary tract infections </strong>due to its <strong>ability to inhibit the adhesion of E. coli </strong>to the <strong>urinary tract lining</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:&nbsp;</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Journal- Inhibitory activity of cranberry extract on the bacterial adhesiveness in the urine of women: An ex-vivo study&rsquo;. Int. journal of immunopathology and pharmacology, Tempera et al 2010-23 (2): 611&ndash;8.</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
